<div class="page-content">

    <h1>NightSkyHigh</h1>

    <h2><i>"Lets light up and watch the light show."</i></h2>

    <img src="/images/artwork/suitme.webp" alt="NightSkyHigh artwork" width="892" height="492">

    <p>
        NightSkyHigh is a mix of astronomy, telescope photography,
        planets, moons, strange cosmic thoughts, ridiculous humour,
        and staring into space wondering what the hell is really going on.
    </p>

    <p>
        It started as “A STONER ME…DOIN...ASTRONOMY” but slowly evolved
        into something much bigger:
        part astronomy project,
        part art project,
        part comedy,
        part cosmic existential crisis.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>What Is Astronomy?</h2>

    <p>
        The art of looking up and not on Google...the irony..!!!
    </p>

    <p>
        Astronomy is the study of planets, moons, stars, galaxies,
        gravity, light, time, black holes, and distances so large
        they stop making sense to the human brain.
    </p>

    <img src="/images/artwork/lookup.png" alt="Looking into space" width="892" height="492">

    <hr>

    <h2>The Scale Of Space</h2>

    <p>
        One of the strangest things about astronomy is scale.
    </p>

    <p>
        Everything in everyday life feels large to us...
        buildings, cities, oceans, countries...
        but compared to space, Earth itself is tiny.
    </p>

    <h3>Earth</h3>

    <img src="/images/artwork/earth.webp" alt="Earth">

    <p>
        Earth is our home.
        Every person who has ever lived existed on this tiny world.
    </p>

    <h3>The Solar System</h3>

    <img src="/images/artwork/solar.webp" alt="Solar System">

    <p>
        If Earth were the size of a pea,
        the Solar System would still stretch for metres.
    </p>

    <p>
        The distances between planets are enormous.
        Space is mostly emptiness.
    </p>

    <h3>The Milky Way Galaxy</h3>

    <img src="/images/artwork/galaxy.webp" alt="Milky Way Galaxy">

    <p>
        Our Solar System is only one tiny system inside the Milky Way galaxy,
        which contains hundreds of billions of stars.
    </p>

    <p>
        If the Solar System were reduced to the size of a pea,
        the Milky Way would be roughly the size of Europe.
    </p>

    <h3>The Observable Universe</h3>

    <img src="/images/artwork/universe.webp" alt="Observable Universe">

    <p>
        The observable universe contains billions of galaxies,
        each containing billions of stars,
        stretching across distances almost impossible to imagine.
    </p>

    <p>
        If the Milky Way galaxy were reduced to the size of a pea,
        the observable universe would be roughly the size of Earth itself.
    </p>

    <p>
        Beyond that may exist even more universe,
        perhaps infinitely more.
        Nobody truly knows.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Planet Tracker</h2>

    <p>
        Planet Tracker is the structured side of the project.
    </p>

    <p>
        It explores the planets and moons of our Solar System,
        mixing real astronomy with visuals, facts, interaction,
        and eventually user-created content.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Moon Photography</h2>

    <p>
        The moon gallery contains real telescope photography
        taken through my own telescope over time.
    </p>

    <p>
        Some images are rough.
        Some are better.
        That is part of the point:
        you can see the learning process happen.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>James Webb And Deep Space</h2>

    <img src="/images/artwork/jamesw1.jpg" alt="James Webb Telescope image" width="192" height="150">

    <p>
        Modern telescopes like James Webb allow humanity
        to look deeper into space than ever before.
    </p>

    <p>
        Many of the glowing regions in these images are star-forming regions,
        dense with gas, dust, heat, gravity, and light.
    </p>

    <p>
        Some of the light in these images began travelling
        before human civilisation even existed.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>The Tone Of NightSkyHigh</h2>

    <p>
        NightSkyHigh is not trying to be a formal science institution.
    </p>

    <p>
        It is astronomy with personality:
        telescope photos,
        weird humour,
        cosmic scale,
        stories,
        strange thoughts,
        and the occasional completely stupid joke.
    </p>

    <p>
        Somewhere between science,
        art,
        curiosity,
        and madness.
    </p>

    <p>
        Light up, look up,
        and enjoy the light show.
    </p>

</div>